{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἐξᾰπᾰτάω</b>, <br /> <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>iterative</i> ἐξαπάτασκον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 1070 (hexameter)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <i>future</i> <b>-απατηθήσομαι</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 499c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but -απατήσομαι in <i>passive</i> sense, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 7.3.3 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>deceive</b> or <b>beguile, deceive thoroughly,</b> εἴτινά που.. ἔτι ἔλπεται ἐξαπατήσειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.371, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.414, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 1.29, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.153, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 901, etc.; ἐ. τινὰ φρένας [prev. author] “Pax” 1099 (hexameter); ἐ. καὶ φενακίζειν 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.204 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <b>seduce</b> a woman, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.114: with double _accusative_, ἐ. τινά τι\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>in</b> a thing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 3.1.19; also ἐ. ἐπὶ τοῖς ἰδίοις συμβολαίοις 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 10.7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; περὶ σαυτὸν ποιεῖσθαι.. ἐφ᾽ οἷς ἐξαπατᾷς ἔλεον surround yourself with compassion for your <b>swindling tricks,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.196 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἐ. τινὰ ὡς.. <b>cheat</b> him <b>into believing</b> that.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 5.7.6, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 413d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐ. νόσον <b>beguile</b> or <b>assuage</b> it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Nig